div.p:
I ſpare to ſpeake what further right you haue in mee, and how much I am beholding (in my particular) to the example of your integrity and conſcionable courſe of life, of your great and continuall paines, humility, and modeſty euery way, you being as eminent in and for humilitie, as humble in eminency of gifts. But I dare not preſume to preſſe theſe while I praiſe them: I know you had rather ſo bee, then be knowne to bee, further then Gods glory and the neceſſity of the Church requires; and ſo you neither are nor can be vnknowne. I will conclude, propounding the example of your wonderfull diligence and conſtant paines, as alſo modeſty, to ſuch as in the Miniſtery ſeeke their owne eaſe, and follow their pleaſures, and by the Miniſtery ſeeke dignities and preferments to themſelues. Doubtleſſe labouring with like ſingleneſſe of heart and modeſty of minde, they ſhould finde little cauſe to doubt ſo much of Gods Prouidence, as to deſpaire of Prouiſion proportionable to their gifts. You haue found it vnſought
for, but ſhall finde the fruit and reward much more hereafter. 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 . I will not preſume to ſtirre vp you, but my ſelfe, and other ſluggards, in and with the words of Ignatius, Ignat. epiſt. 1. to one Mary,
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 . And thus I end.
